04986nam a22008055i 9780231536080DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013002987  a(OCoLC)872641884  a97802315360807 a10.7312/kinn163082doi  a(DE-B1597)458395  a(OCoLC)871681956  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aCT3710b.L5813 2014 4aCT3710 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a920.05100aExemplary Women of Early China :bThe Lienü zhuan of Liu Xiang. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranslations from the Asian Classics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChronology -- t1. The Maternal Models -- t2. The Worthy and Enlightened -- t3. The Sympathetic and Wise -- t4. The Chaste and Compliant -- t5. The Principled and Righteous -- t6. The Accomplished Rhetoricians -- t7. The Depraved and Favored -- t8. Supplementary Biographies -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn early China, was it correct for a woman to disobey her father, contradict her husband, or shape the public policy of a son who ruled over a dynasty or state? According to the Lienü zhuan, or Categorized Biographies of Women, it was not only appropriate but necessary for women to step in with wise counsel when fathers, husbands, or rulers strayed from the path of virtue. Compiled toward the end of the Former Han dynasty (202 BCE-9 CE) by Liu Xiang (79-8 BCE), the Lienü zhuan is the earliest extant book in the Chinese tradition solely devoted to the education of women. Far from providing a unified vision of women's roles, the text promotes a diverse and sometimes contradictory range of practices. At one extreme are exemplars resorting to suicide and self-mutilation as a means to preserve chastity and ritual orthodoxy. At the other are bold and outspoken women whose rhetorical mastery helps correct erring rulers, sons, and husbands. The text provides a fascinating overview of the representation of women's roles in early legends, formal speeches on statecraft, and highly fictionalized historical accounts during this foundational period of Chinese history.Over time, the biographies of women became a regular feature of dynastic and local histories and a vehicle for expressing and transmitting concerns about women's social, political, and domestic roles. The Lienü zhuan is also rich in information about the daily life, rituals, and domestic concerns of early China. Inspired by its accounts, artists across the millennia have depicted its stories on screens, paintings, lacquer ware, murals, and stone relief sculpture, extending its reach to literate and illiterate audiences alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aKvinnorxBiografixKina. 0aKvinnorxLivsföringxKinaxChina. 0aWomenxBiographyxChina. 0aWomenxConduct of lifexChina. 0aWomenxConduct of life. 0aWomenzChinavBiography. 0aWomenzChinaxConduct of life. 0aWomen. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aKinney, Anne Behnke.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kinn1630840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231536080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231536080.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL